				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$y(\theta _{02})$$\end{document}y(θ02) describe different output trajectories. By a differential algebra approach, Piazzola et al. (2021) have shown that the following deterministic SIR model with its output25\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \left\{ \begin{array}{llll} \frac{dI_t}{dt}=\beta _0 I_t (N-I_t-R_t) - \gamma _0 I_t\\ \frac{dR_t}{dt}=\gamma _0 I_t\\ y_{1,t} = \frac{1}{K} I_t\\ y_{2,t} = \frac{1}{K} R_t\\ \end{array}\right. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}dItdt=β0It(N-It-Rt)-γ0ItdRtdt=γ0Ity1,t=1KIty2,t=1KRtdefined for a non-normalised population of size N, is structurally identifiable with respect to the unknown parameters \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
